CM_ BO_ 377 "i_VehicleSpeed: Pre-facelift (Rhys Morgan HsInfo.js). UNCONFIRMED on facelift cluster -- transmitting at any tested value produces no speedometer response.";

CM_ BO_ 523 "u_SpeedCandidate_0x20B: Byte-level analysis of the L322 candump (378 samples, ~15ms interval): byte0=0xC3 static, byte2=0x87 static. byte1 is a 15-value rolling counter (0x03-0x11, wraps). byte4 = (byte1-3)*4 -- derived/redundant, likely a freshness check. byte3/byte5 form a SEPARATE, much slower counter pair: baseline byte3=0xFF/byte5=0x00, then byte3=0xFE/byte5=0x01, then byte3=0xFD/byte5=0x02 (byte3 = 0xFF - N, byte5 = N) -- only reaches N=2 over ~6 seconds while the source vehicle is stationary. Working theory: this is a raw WHEEL-PULSE counter (ticking from idle-engine vibration on the tone ring, not real rotation), not a direct speed magnitude -- i.e. a differentiate-over-time signal like a real ABS/wheel-speed module would send, structurally similar to how 0x3EB gates trust in other DSC data. Bench test: replaying this pattern changed the speedometer from pegged-at-max (no 0x20B present) to holding at 0 -- consistent with the cluster wanting to see counter *movement* rather than a static magnitude in 0x29B. NEXT TEST: run 0x20B with its counter incrementing (even arbitrarily) together with 0x29B bytes 6-7 set nonzero, check whether the needle now tracks a plausible value instead of holding at 0. MAJOR UPDATE: bench test with byte7=0x88 (bytes6-7 = 00 88) caused RAW speed to flicker between 0 and 136, displaying ~1.2-2.1 mph. 136/64 = 2.125 -- matches the upper display bound closely. Working formula: bytes 6-7 as big-endian 16-bit raw value, mph = raw/64 (or close to it -- needs a second data point at a different value to confirm the exact divisor and check linearity). The 0-vs-136 FLICKER is the open problem -- consistent with the cluster only trusting the frame intermittently, the same pattern seen with every other gating signal on this project (0x088, 0x295, 0x3F3 all needed a specific counter/freshness byte before being trusted continuously). Candidate causes: the existing byte1 fast counter (0x03-0x11 wrap) or byte3/byte5 slow counter may need to align with the speed value in a specific way not yet reproduced, or a completely separate freshness mechanism is needed for bytes 6-7 specifically. NEXT TEST: try varying RESEND_INTERVAL_MS or decoupling the speed update rate from the counter update rate to see if the flicker resolves. FLICKER CAUSE IDENTIFIED: was a bus collision between two of the user''s own test scripts (a separate script sending all-zeros to 0x20B was running at the same time as this one) -- NOT a cluster trust/freshness issue as speculated. Confirmed clean once the competing script was stopped. CLEAN DATA POINT: bytes 6-7 = 0x50, 0x50 (raw=0x5050=20560 either byte order, since both bytes match) displays 133.4 mph / 214.7 kph, no flicker. The earlier 136-raw/~2.1mph data point was captured DURING the flicker/collision and is likely contaminated -- ratio check (136/2.1=65 vs 20560/133.4=154) doesn''t hold a consistent scale, so treat that first point as unreliable rather than trying to fit both. Formula still UNDETERMINED with only one clean point, and this test can''t distinguish big-endian vs little-endian since byte6=byte7=0x50. NEXT TEST: use distinct byte6/byte7 values (e.g. 0x01, 0x00) to determine byte order, plus 2-3 more speed values to fit an actual scale/offset. FORMULA DERIVED from a 17-point user-supplied calibration table spanning 0x000F to 0x7FFF: mph = raw * 0.0064310 + 1.20 (linear fit, residuals within +/-0.05 mph on 16 of 17 points). bytes 6-7 as a 16-bit value (byte order not independently distinguished, but consistent with big-endian given earlier single-byte test). OUTLIER: 0x7FFF (32767) predicts ~212 mph from this formula but measures 194.1 mph -- likely a display-side clamp/cap (194 mph plausible max digital-speedo readout) rather than a break in the encoding, and 0x7FFF is also the max positive int16 value, a common firmware sentinel -- not fully explained, flagged rather than dismissed. Formula fits tightly enough to treat as reliable for encoding test speeds, pending independent re-verification. REFINED with 3 more data points near the top: 0x7000->185.6, 0x70FF->187.2, 0x74FF->193.8 -- ALL match the formula closely (e.g. 0x74FF predicts 193.8, exact). This means the formula is accurate up to at least 193.8 mph, and the earlier 0x7FFF outlier is confirmed to be a genuine DISPLAY CLAMP around ~194 mph, not a formula breakdown -- the clamp threshold sits somewhere between raw 29951 (193.8, matches formula) and raw 32767 (194.1, far below the ~212 the formula would predict). Consistent with a much earlier bench finding where a different 0x3EB payload was separately observed pegging the speedo to ''194 mph'' -- likely the same hard display cap, not a coincidence. Formula can now be treated as reliable across the full practical speed range up to the ~194 mph clamp.";
CM_ BO_ 533 "i_ChargingSystemFault_0x215: STRONG CANDIDATE for the BATTERY NOT CHARGING / Generator Failure fault. Sourced from L322/L405 CAN code docs, byte0 mask 0x40 = ~charging system fault (battery) -- tilde convention elsewhere in these docs means the bit reads inverted (i.e. clear the bit to indicate a fault is present, or vice versa -- needs bench confirmation either way). NOT yet tested. Context: user found a large voltage mismatch on the bench -- physical/local battery reading ~623 (raw ADC, matches ETM test 22 LOCAL) vs cluster-reported VEHICLE battery voltage ~1200 -- almost certainly the actual trigger for this fault, likely via whatever frame carries VEHICLE battery voltage (not yet identified separately from this fault-bit candidate). Sits immediately next to 0x20B in the L322/L405 HS CAN ID list.";
CM_ BO_ 535 "c_HSHeartbeat: Constant payload 00 03 FF 00 7F FF 00 00, ~8ms interval. Cluster-originated -- observe only, do not transmit on a live bus with the cluster present.";
CM_ BO_ 580 "u_NightLight_0x244: UNCONFIRMED, sourced from forum discussion (no direct citation given, treat as third-hand until traced to source). Claimed: byte0=0xF7 + byte1=0x40 = night light ON; byte0=0x00 + byte1=0x40 = night light OFF. Not yet bench-tested on the XF250 cluster.";
CM_ BO_ 599 "c_RTCClock: Cluster-originated real-time clock broadcast, ~40ms interval. Byte 0/1/2 purpose not fully decoded (byte 0 = 0xFF likely invalid/uninitialised flag).";

CM_ BO_ 661 "c_RPM_0x295: CONFIRMED, facelift XF250. Bytes 6-7 (BE): raw16 = 0x8000 + rpm (rpm < 0x2000). byte5 = 0xFF - byte7 (verified across 284+ samples). Re-confirmed via a fresh bench log (1783240316614_RPM.csv): manually replaying the frame blipped the tach to exactly 724 RPM repeatedly (0x82D4 & 0x1FFF = 0x02D4 = 724), matching the original decode exactly. Requires 0x4D5 (ECM presence) to be trusted -- without it, RPM RAW reads as the invalid sentinel in ETM regardless of what''s sent on 0x295 itself.";
CM_ BO_ 665 "u_GearKnobModule_0x299: From the same facelift logs. Completely static payload (00 00 00 00 00 00 18 74) across all observed gear states and the wake sequence, ~65-100ms interval. Undecoded -- possibly a module identity/capability frame rather than a state broadcast, given it never changes.";
CM_ BO_ 667 "c_EBD_Status_0x29B: CONFIRMED by bench test -- payload 3F FE 00 70 20 03 00 00 clears the EBD FAULT warning. Also involved in clearing the BRAKE warning indicator, but that required BOTH this frame AND shorting pins 1 & 25 on cluster connector B (the Brake Fluid Switch, normally-closed) -- the brake warning is not resolved by CAN data alone, it also needs the physical brake fluid level switch satisfied. This exact payload matches the static baseline this project had already been using for 0x29B before this confirmation (previously logged as unconfirmed/no-effect-alone in earlier isolation tests -- now confirmed effective, at least for EBD, once combined with other frames now active (0x3EB, 0x39A, 0x3F3, etc.) and/or the physical brake switch fix). Speed encoding in bytes 6-7 (currently 0x00 0x00) still unconfirmed for its own sake -- this promotion is specifically for the EBD/brake warning effect, not a claim that speed itself is solved.";
CM_ BO_ 672 "i_GearKnobStatus_0x2A0: From the same facelift XF250 gear-knob logs as 0x3F3/0x312, NOT yet independently bench-tested. ~1.6-1.8ms interval (fast). byte0 static 0x00, byte1 is a 15-value rolling counter (0x60-0x6E), byte2 = byte1 + 0x22 (constant offset), byte3 static 0x00, byte7 static 0x21 regardless of gear. Bytes 4-6 carry gear state, two combos observed: Park = 80 FF 7F, Reverse-ish = 00 FE FF (captured during a wake/raise/reverse/park sequence -- gear correlation inferred from sequence position, not independently confirmed against a labelled state). Likely a second, faster gear/knob-position broadcast alongside 0x3F3 -- role vs 0x3F3 not yet understood (redundant status vs a different consumer module). CONFIRMED ''not needed'' for core gear-selector function per SomersetEV/LandRover-rotary-gear-change (explicitly marked ''(Not needed)'' with a matching byte table for bytes 3-6). Low priority for further decode work.";

CM_ BO_ 712 "c_ADCM_Status_0x2C8: CONFIRMED by bench test -- drives ADCM (Adaptive Damping Control Module) status. Same FAULTY -> CONNECTED -> MISSING pattern as 0x422/0x35F/0x3CF/0x4D5. Payload content not yet decoded -- presence alone was sufficient.";
CM_ BO_ 786 "i_GearSelectorLock_0x312: CROSS-CONFIRMED by SomersetEV/LandRover-rotary-gear-change (same byte0/1/2 mapping, labelled ''from selector'' i.e. a status response rather than a command). byte7 is documented there as a gear-dependent cycling counter (not static as modeled here) -- each gear''s cycle builds on the previous gear''s count before settling. Not yet incorporated into our own counter logic. The byte1 extra-bit anomaly (0x11/0x21) seen nested inside the 0x422 byte6=0x96 window is now read as a secondary reaction to a Dynamic/Snow mode request rather than a Park Brake/Ignition event (see 0x422 comment) -- video review confirmed neither of those buttons was tested in this session. Per openinverter.org wiki/forum (same source as above): knob lock/unlock is gated by a physical Park/brake-pedal-switch pin (pin 14 on the 22-way connector, pin 10 on the 12-way) -- the community''s own attempts to solve lock/unlock via CAN alone were unsuccessful, suggesting byte1''s lock state may be a status echo of that physical pin rather than something purely CAN-commanded. ETM NOTE: Module Status test shows GSM as FAULTY while TCM shows CONNECTED (with 0x3F3 active but 0x312 disabled/ENABLE_312=false in hs.js) -- user hypothesis: GSM specifically needs 0x312, which hasn''t been enabled yet. Worth testing with ENABLE_312=true to see if GSM moves to CONNECTED. RULED OUT (partial): ENABLE_312 set true on the bench, GSM module status STILL shows FAULTY -- 0x312 alone does not satisfy GSM presence. Other gear-knob-related candidates (0x2A0, 0x299, 0x422) remain untested for this specific purpose -- also possible GSM needs a different signal entirely (e.g. a start-control/SCU-style handshake) not yet identified.";

CM_ BO_ 823 "c_ClusterOwned_DoorStatus_0x337: CONFIRMED cluster-owned (TX by the cluster itself, per user) -- DO NOT TRANSMIT, same category as 0x397/0x457 (risk of bus ID collision). byte2 static at 0x3F on the bench (all doors/trunk/hood shut) -- matches the L322 doc bit table exactly if bits mean ''closed'' when set: mask 0x01=fl door, 0x02=fr door, 0x04=rl door, 0x08=rr door, 0x10=trunk, 0x20=hood -- 0x3F sets all six bits, consistent with a stationary bench setup with everything shut.";
CM_ BO_ 863 "c_ACC_Status_0x35F: CONFIRMED by bench test -- drives ACC (Adaptive Cruise Control) module status. Same state-machine pattern as 0x422->GSM: FAULTY (never sent) -> CONNECTED (enabled) -> MISSING (disabled again). Payload content not yet decoded bit-by-bit -- presence alone was sufficient for this test. RR/XJ doc bits for this ID (0.08 beep, 0.10 beep, cruise control not available) not yet independently verified.";
CM_ BO_ 880 "i_LEDBacklight_0x370: Sourced from a different openinverter.org forum contributor (not Tom-evnut, SomersetEV, or VanGogh) in the same GSM thread, testing a Gen 1 GSM part number JLR GJ32-7E453-AB. byte6 = backlight dimmer (0x00=0%, 0xFF=100%), byte7 = backlight on/off (0x00=off, 0xFF=on). Poster noted they hadn''t found anything else on this ID. Not present in any of our own pulled logs (jag-knob/sport/wake/rotate/awake-lower-knob) -- unconfirmed against our own data, single-source.";

CM_ BO_ 919 "u_Unknown_0x397: Byte 1 alternates 0x80/0x00, byte 5 static 0x3C (60 dec), byte 7 alternates 0x10/0x00. Pattern suggests a status/valid flag pair -- undecoded.";
CM_ BO_ 922 "c_AirbagSeatbelt: CONFIRMED by bench test -- payload 80 00 00 00 00 00 32 0E suppresses both the airbag yellow warning and the seatbelt red warning (user-confirmed, exact bytes). On closer bit inspection this is actually CONSISTENT with the previously modeled bits, not contradictory: byte6=0x32 has bits 0x04 (airbag) and 0x08 (airbag flash) clear, byte7=0x0E has bit 0x01 (belt) clear -- all three read as ''off'', matching suppression. The extra set bits in this real payload (byte0=0x80, byte6 bits 0x02/0x10/0x20, byte7 bits 0x02/0x04/0x08) are additional data not yet modeled -- possibly a counter or other airbag/belt substatus -- worth decoding separately, but they don''t conflict with the airbag/belt bit assignments themselves. Using this exact payload as the confirmed default going forward since it''s the directly-tested one; whether the original simpler all-zero payload also works is unconfirmed (not A/B tested against this one). ETM CONFIRMATION: Module Status test shows RCM (Restraints Control Module) as CONNECTED with this frame active -- confirms this frame satisfies RCM module presence, not just the warning lights.";
CM_ BO_ 975 "c_AFLS_Status_0x3CF: CONFIRMED by bench test -- drives AFLS (Adaptive Front Lighting System) module status. Same FAULTY -> CONNECTED -> MISSING pattern as 0x422/0x35F. Payload content not yet decoded bit-by-bit -- presence alone was sufficient.";

CM_ BO_ 1003 "c_DSC_ABS_Status: CONFIRMED by bench test. Payload 01 01 60 00 00 00 00 00 suppresses ABS, ESP, and DSC warning lights simultaneously. byte1=0x01 (DSC on), byte2=0x60 (ABS OK combo bits 0x40|0x20). byte0=0x01 -- unclear if this value matters or if it still works with byte0=0x00 / a rolling counter, not isolated yet. Individual ESP-active/ESP-flash/ABS-fault bits are inferred from RR/XJ docs, not independently toggled/tested -- only the combined suppress-everything payload has been bench-verified. ''stability control not available'' bit (RR notation '1.07') is ambiguous -- the mask/bit convention doesn't match the rest of this doc's notation and would overlap the confirmed DSC_State field if taken as mask 0x07 -- deliberately not modeled here pending clarification. Beep bit (0x80, byte2) effect unknown. NEW DATA POINT (VanGogh, forums.moderndaymods.com ''Gear Shift Module (GSM)'' thread -- VanGogh is a DIFFERENT person from Tom-evnut, the gear-knob repo author; both were active in the same openinverter.org GSM thread but are separate contributors): a simple table gives byte1=0x00, byte2=0xAA as ''LED DSC off'' and byte1=0x00, byte2=0x00 as ''LED DSC on'' -- rest of payload zero in both. This does NOT obviously reconcile with our own bench-confirmed suppress-everything combo (byte1=0x01, byte2=0x60) -- 0xAA (1010 1010) shares no bits with 0x60 (0110 0000). Possible explanations: (a) ''LED DSC'' in that table refers to a physical DSC-OFF button indicator on the console/GSM module, not the cluster''s ABS/DSC warning icons -- a different consumer of the same ID; (b) byte2 is a small enum rather than independent bits and both data points are correct for different things it controls. Not yet bench-tested against the XF250 cluster specifically -- worth an isolated test with byte1=0x00 and byte2=0xAA/0x00 to see what, if anything, changes on the cluster itself. PROVENANCE NOTE: the ''LED DSC on/off'' video evidence is from a separate physical module (the GSM/gear-shift-module console itself, with its own DSC button and backlight), tested standalone by a different person (VanGogh) ~3 years ago -- this project does not have that GSM hardware, only the XF250 cluster. Whether this byte2 value does anything to the CLUSTER''s own ABS/DSC warning icon (separate from the GSM button''s backlight) is unverified and can only be checked on our own bench, not inferred from that video. RE-CONFIRMED verbatim by the user''s own bench payload [0x00, 0x01, 0x60, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00] -- byte2 mask 0x60 specifically turns off the ABS light (direct user confirmation, not just inferred from the RR/XJ combo table). MAJOR NEW FINDING: byte0 is NOT inert as previously assumed. Payload [0x01, 0x01, 0x60, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00, 0x00] (byte0=0x01, vs the earlier confirmed byte0=0x00 combo) sets the digital speedo to 194 mph. In ETM mode, RAW speed drops from 0xFFFF+1/65536 (the invalid/no-data sentinel) to a fixed 30001 with this payload present -- but fuzzing bytes 4-7 does not change that value further, and it does not track anything dynamically. Working theory: this frame is MISSING A ROLLING COUNTER -- the cluster may accept it as a one-time valid snapshot (moving RAW off the invalid sentinel) but then holds that value rather than trusting continued live data, consistent with every other gating frame on this project needing a counter to be trusted as live (0x088, 0x295, 0x3F3, etc.). NOT yet resolved. Separately: RPM RAW was also observed at 65536 (invalid sentinel) in ETM during this same test -- 0x295 was likely not active in that test, not necessarily related to this byte0 finding, but flagged for the record. NEXT STEP: try adding a rolling counter to byte0 or another undetermined byte and see if RAW speed starts tracking instead of holding at a fixed value. ETM CONFIRMATION: Module Status test shows DSC as CONNECTED with this frame active -- direct confirmation this frame satisfies the DSC module presence check, not just the warning light.";

CM_ BO_ 1011 "c_HS_TSM_GearPosition_0x3F3: ID is ECU-to-gear-selector gear-state/status broadcast (historically labelled 'tester' during reverse engineering). CONFIRMED per-gear byte table, sourced from genuine facelift XF250 gear-knob candumps (Tom-evnut/Land-Rover-Gearknob repo -- main log 16205 rows, plus a dedicated Sport log and the author's own findings spreadsheet).

Gear-specific values:
  Park:    byte0=5C byte1=66 byte4=FF byte5=7F byte6=00 byte7=80
  Reverse: byte0=7C byte1=24 byte4=FE byte5=FF byte6=01 byte7=00
  Neutral: byte0=7C byte1=25 byte4=FD byte5=FF byte6=02 byte7=00
  Drive:   byte0=7C byte1=24 byte4=FB byte5=FF byte6=04 byte7=00
  Sport:   byte0=7C byte1=24 byte4=F7 byte5=FF byte6=08 byte7=00

Confirmed status bits:
- byte0 mask 0x10 must be set to avoid Gearbox Fault.
- byte1 mask 0x04 must be set to avoid Gearbox Fault.
- byte2 mask 0x20 = Gearbox Overheating.
- byte2 mask 0x01 = Manual Shift Disabled.

byte1=0x24 is shared by Reverse/Drive/Sport; byte4/byte6 are what actually distinguish those gears.

byte2 upper nibble carries status flags while the lower nibble is a free-running 4-bit counter cycling 0x0-0xE before wrapping (15-state cycle). byte3 = byte2 plus a gear-dependent offset:
  Park    +0x82
  Reverse +0x03
  Neutral +0x04
  Drive   +0x06
  Sport   +0x0A

Corresponding byte3 ranges:
  Park    0x82-0x90
  Reverse 0x03-0x11
  Neutral 0x04-0x12
  Drive   0x06-0x14
  Sport   0x0A-0x18

A user-captured PARK frame on the bench (1C 26 00 82 FF 7F 00 80) matched byte4/5/6/7 and correctly set the IPC gear indicator to P.

Cross-confirmed by SomersetEV/LandRover-rotary-gear-change, which contains an identical gear table. That project labels this frame as originating from the transmission ECU rather than a tester. Functional notes from that source indicate bytes 0, 4, 5 and 6 are required to raise the GSM rotary knob, while byte1 is not required for knob raise and does not affect the illuminated gear indicator.

PROVENANCE NOTE: the knob raise/lower and selector illumination behaviour described above refers to the physical GSM console from third-party testing and has not been verified on this project's own hardware. The gear-state byte values themselves are directly bench-confirmed for driving the IPC gear display.";


CM_ BO_ 1024 "i_CCF_Block1_0x400: Mirrored by IPC from MS bus to HS bus. Part of the JLR Car Configuration File (CCF) broadcast -- Block One, EUCD platform. byte0 = line number within the CCF (the frame cycles through sequential lines, not a single static payload -- matches the multi-step transition pattern observed in candump analysis). Not yet independently probed for effects -- 0x401 (Block Two) is where the confirmed TPMS effect and VIN data live, see that message''s comment.";
CM_ BO_ 1025 "c_CCF_Block2_0x401: Part of the JLR Car Configuration File (CCF) broadcast -- Block Two, T5 platform. byte0 = line number within the CCF. Lines 01/02/03 contain the VIN (line 01 starts with vehicle type e.g. L359, brand e.g. Land Rover, model year e.g. 14). CONFIRMED by direct bench test: this frame creates and clears the tire pressure (TPMS) warning -- exact line/byte within the CCF not yet isolated, only that the overall frame is responsible (0x504, 0x503, and 0x396 were all tested and ruled out). MAJOR FINDING: modifying CCF content and feeding it to the FCDIM (display/MMI module) changes which vehicle software identity it loads -- e.g. switching between Range Rover and Jaguar configurations. This is a shared JLR display platform mechanism, not XF250-specific -- worth treating CCF content with real care given it can reconfigure what the display module believes it is. NEXT STEP: isolate which specific CCF line/byte controls the TPMS warning specifically, rather than replaying the whole block. LINE 0x1C CONFIRMED by direct bench test: byte3 mask 0x80 = Blind Spot Monitor Not Available, byte3 mask 0x02 = Tire Pressure System Fault. This is the specific line/byte within the CCF broadcast responsible for the TPMS and BSM warnings (see hs_bus.dbc for the per-line trigger/clear payload table already extracted from candumpStartup.log vs candump-2020-04-24_130142.log for this same line). Resolves the earlier open question of exactly which CCF line controls these warnings. IMPORTANT NUANCE (ETM): even with this frame''s TPMS-fault bit cleared and the warning icon suppressed, ETM Module Status test still shows TPMS as FAULTY -- confirms warning-suppression and module-presence are SEPARATE mechanisms. This frame only handles the icon; making TPMS itself show CONNECTED would need a genuine TPMS module status frame, not yet found (separate open problem, not solved by the CCF fix).";
CM_ BO_ 1029 "JLR Vehicle Status 0x404 multiplexed message. Mux 0x02 carries battery voltage at byte 4, scale 0.25V. Mux 0x10/0x11/0x12 carry VIN ASCII segments.";
CM_ BO_ 1028 "JLR Vehicle Status 0x405 multiplexed message. Mux 0x02 carries battery voltage at byte 4, scale 0.25V. Mux 0x10/0x11/0x12 carry VIN ASCII segments.";
CM_ BO_ 1031 "c_CCF_Block2_0x401: Mirrored by IPC from MS bus to HS bus. Part of the JLR Car Configuration File (CCF) broadcast -- Block Two, T5 platform. byte0 = line number within the CCF. Lines 01/02/03 contain the VIN (line 01 starts with vehicle type e.g. L359, brand e.g. Land Rover, model year e.g. 14). CONFIRMED by direct bench test: this frame creates and clears the tire pressure (TPMS) warning -- exact line/byte within the CCF not yet isolated, only that the overall frame is responsible (0x504, 0x503, and 0x396 were all tested and ruled out). MAJOR FINDING: modifying CCF content and feeding it to the FCDIM (display/MMI module) changes which vehicle software identity it loads -- e.g. switching between Range Rover and Jaguar configurations. This is a shared JLR display platform mechanism, not XF250-specific -- worth treating CCF content with real care given it can reconfigure what the display module believes it is. NEXT STEP: isolate which specific CCF line/byte controls the TPMS warning specifically, rather than replaying the whole block. LINE 0x1C CONFIRMED by direct bench test: byte3 mask 0x80 = Blind Spot Monitor Not Available, byte3 mask 0x02 = Tire Pressure System Fault. This is the specific line/byte within the CCF broadcast responsible for the TPMS and BSM warnings (see hs_bus.dbc for the per-line trigger/clear payload table already extracted from candumpStartup.log vs candump-2020-04-24_130142.log for this same line). Resolves the earlier open question of exactly which CCF line controls these warnings. IMPORTANT NUANCE (ETM): even with this frame''s TPMS-fault bit cleared and the warning icon suppressed, ETM Module Status test still shows TPMS as FAULTY -- confirms warning-suppression and module-presence are SEPARATE mechanisms. This frame only handles the icon; making TPMS itself show CONNECTED would need a genuine TPMS module status frame, not yet found (separate open problem, not solved by the CCF fix).";

CM_ BO_ 1058 "c_HS_GSM_ETM_Status_DynamicWinterModeRequest_0x422: ETM/GSM status and LCD message request frame. Byte 6 contains a bitfield used by the IPC to request Terrain Response / Dynamic Mode LCD messages (Racing Flag icon). Confirmed message combinations:
- b6.7 = Program Temporarily Unavailable.
- b6.5 = Recommend Winter Mode For Conditions.
- b6.4 + b6.1 = Winter Mode Confirmed.
- b6.4 + b6.3 = Mode Change In Progress.
- b6.4 + b6.2 + b6.1 = Dynamic Mode Confirmed.
- b6.7 + b6.5 = Program Re-Activated.
- b6.7 + b6.4 = Dynamic Mode Fault.

Bits are currently exposed individually because the IPC interprets combinations rather than independent signals.

Observed values: 0x60 = Park; 0x67 = any non-Park gear. Believed to be a status echo of the physical IGN-pin / rotary knob position rather than a CAN command. Bench and community evidence indicate the knob raise/lower mechanism on Gen 1 GSM units is controlled by the IGN input pin, not by CAN. Transmitting frame 0x422 is required for GSM module presence, but the specific byte 7 value tested does not affect the module-status check.";


CM_ BO_ 1111 "u_Unknown_0x457: Bytes 0/1 vary, bytes 2/5/7 stable (0x66/0x60/0x6C). Undecoded. Additional observation: byte2=0x00 has been associated with 'Blue light off' state in one dataset; no corresponding 'on' state confirmed. Possible lighting indicator (DRL/high-beam/aux).";
CM_ BO_ 1117 "u_Unknown_0x45D: Three observed states, bytes 5/6 stable (0x05/0x47). Undecoded.";
CM_ BO_ 1143 "i_ESCL_SteeringLock_0x477: STRONG CANDIDATE for the ESCL/steering-column-lock status this project needs -- this project has no physical ESCL module, only the cluster, so this frame would need to be emulated. Sourced from L322/XJ/L405 CAN code docs (''minimum for tidy''), NOT yet bench-tested. Byte/bit layout: bytes 0-3 possibly carry a fuel-related value (''0-3 fuel'', notation ambiguous, may overlap with the separate 0x068 fuel mechanism -- needs clarification). byte6 (''6.x'' notation): mask 0x01 = STEERING COLUMN LOCKED, mask 0x08 = engine stop button pressed, mask 0x10 = ignition is on (possibly redundant with the already-confirmed 0x07D ignition state), mask 0x40 = washer fluid low. byte7: smart key status bits (0x4=not found, 0x8=recognized-press-brake, 0xC=check smart key per L322; XJ additionally lists 0x10=transmission not in park, 0x20=press brake when starting). PRIORITY TEST: try transmitting this frame with the steering-column-locked bit CLEAR (0) and ignition-on bit set to match real state, to see if it satisfies whatever is latching the STEERING COLUMN LOCKED fault -- per the workshop manual PDF, this fault also blocks engine start, matching the reported symptom. BENCH TESTED: NO EFFECT on STEERING COLUMN LOCKED with the steering-locked bit clear and ignition-on set. User hypothesis: the 0x4xx range in this doc family may be status-only broadcasts (i.e. something the cluster or another module transmits outward, not something an external device can inject to change behaviour) -- consistent with 0x397/0x457/0x337 all turning out to be cluster-owned in this same ID neighbourhood. NEXT CHECK: verify Rx/Tx direction for 0x477 the same way as those (does it already appear as Rx from the cluster when not transmitted?) before pursuing this ID further for ESCL.";
CM_ BO_ 1149 "u_Unknown_0x47D: Burst pattern at startup only, settles to 00 00 BF 00 18 00 00 00. Undecoded.";

CM_ BO_ 1205 "c_ASL_LED_0x4B5: CONFIRMED toggle, sourced from VanGogh/GSM forum table (forums.moderndaymods.com). VanGogh is a different person from Tom-evnut (gear-knob repo author) -- both posted in the same openinverter.org GSM thread but are separate contributors. byte3=0x00 = ASL LED off, byte3=0x80 = ASL LED on, rest of payload zero in both. ASL likely ''Adaptive/Automatic Speed Limiter''. Not yet independently bench-tested on the XF250 facelift cluster. PROVENANCE NOTE: same as 0x3EB -- this is the GSM console''s own ASL button backlight, on hardware we don''t have, tested by someone else years ago. Not verified against the XF250 cluster''s own displays/icons.";
CM_ BO_ 1237 "c_ECM_Status_0x4D5: CONFIRMED by bench test -- drives ECM module status (same FAULTY -> CONNECTED -> MISSING pattern). MAJOR CROSS-DEPENDENCY: also required for RPM (0x295) to be trusted -- ETM RPM RAW reads the invalid sentinel without this frame present, regardless of 0x295 content. ALSO enables the fuel rolling count (previously logged as broken/invalid in ETM Rolling Counts test) -- this may fully explain that earlier issue without 0x513 needing an internal counter of its own; revisit once 0x4D5 is part of the standard baseline. Sample payload from bench log: 02 A7 24 0C 60 F4 92 28 (settled/repeated value) -- byte0 and byte2 showed minor variation earlier in the same log (04/02, 3C/41/A7, 28/27/25/24), structure not yet decoded. ALSO CARRIES ENGINE TEMPERATURE: not sending this frame causes an Engine Temperature Indication Fault and lights the MIL lamp -- matches the workshop manual PDF (''ENGINE TEMPERATURE INDICATION FAULT: engine temperature signal is no longer being received''). Exact byte/bit for the temperature value not yet isolated within this frame''s undecoded structure.";
CM_ BO_ 1279 "c_RTCTimestamp: Cluster-originated, ~170ms interval, increments ~4 ticks/sec during capture (sub-second resolution counter, not a 1Hz tick).";

CM_ SG_ 1279 c_UnixTimestamp "Cluster's stored RTC as Unix epoch seconds, big-endian. Confirms 0x257 HH:MM:SS. NOTE: on first power-up after extended storage this reflects the last time the cluster saw a live RTC source (e.g. ~2018 on a unit unused since then) -- not the current date/time.";
CM_ SG_ 1297 i_InitState_b1 "HS-side cluster init state machine. Observed sequence: alternates 0x01/0x02 (~10 frames) then locks to 0x04. NOT the same as MS-bus 0x511 (fuel display enable) -- same ID, different bus, different meaning, different direction.";
